30.32	Czochralski_process	Czochralski process	The Czochralski process is a method of crystal growth used to obtain single crystals of semiconductors (e.g. silicon, germanium and gallium arsenide), metals (e.g. palladium, platinum, silver, gold), salts, and synthetic gemstones. The process is named after Polish scientist Jan Czochralski, who discovered the method in 1916 while investigating the crystallization rates of metals.	http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6e/Czochralski_Process.svg/350px-Czochralski_Process.svg.png
